Even as Japan frets about the severity of its COVID-19 epidemic, neighboring South Korea is bracing itself for the fallout. South Korea's Health Ministry said "the epidemic has entered a new phase" , while President Moon jae-in said "desperate times call for desperate measures. ".

South Korea's Central Epidemic Prevention Strategy Headquarters on February 18 reported that South Korea added a new case of pneumonia, a cumulative total of 31 cases. The 31st case, a 61-year-old Korean woman with no travel experience, was diagnosed after being tested at the health station in Shoucheng district of Daegu city. She is currently being treated under isolation at the Taegu Hospital. Her condition is not yet known. The Department of Health and epidemic prevention is investigating the patient's route of infection and contacts.

In addition, the infection pathways of the 29th and 30th patients diagnosed on the 16th are also under investigation. They are a husband and wife, has not traveled abroad, nor with other confirmed patients contact, infection path unknown.

At a regular press conference on the 18th, Jeong eun-kyung, the head of the Central Epidemic Prevention Department of the South Korean Ministry of Disease Management, said it was still difficult to determine whether the three cases were related to epidemiological factors, but if the scope of the case definition was expanded, with more tests, more patients are likely to show up. She stressed that the health sector in the entry of quarantine, contact with the self-isolation and other response programmes, while the community to develop prevention and control of the spread of the epidemic response.

Zheng Yinjing said that from the domestic and foreign epidemic situation, the new pneumonia epidemic situation has entered the new situation.

That morning, a 30-year-old man in South Korea died of suspected new pneumonia. According to Yonhap, the man's lungs were found to have signs of bleeding and pneumonia. The man travelled to Henan with his family last month. Epidemiological investigations are under way to ascertain whether the man is infected with NCP.

In addition, the South Korean president's special plane "Air Force 3" has flown to Japan on the 18th to evacuate overseas Chinese from the "Diamond Princess" cruise ship, which has been hit by a new outbreak of pneumonia, the four South Korean citizens and one Japanese family member who will be returned will remain in isolation for another 14 days. There have been no reported cases of infection among Korean citizens on board.

So far, South Korea confirmed 31 patients with 12 out of the hospital, most of the remaining patients in stable condition. In addition to the confirmed cases, 9,234 people were tested for the new coronavirus nucleic acid, 8,277 were negative, and 957 were pending results.

The Central Epidemic Prevention Countermeasures Department said Wednesday that South Korea will put the new pneumonia into the "severe acute respiratory system infectious disease surveillance system" from the 18th, strengthen the prevention and treatment efforts, and further grasp the incidence of infection and pathogen information.

NCP is also included in the "influenza and respiratory viral pathogen infection surveillance system" , which operates as a seasonal influenza surveillance system and currently detects eight viruses.

Zheng said the government will expand the scope of detection of the new coronavirus, build community and medical surveillance system, early detection and timely isolation of patients, to prevent the spread of the epidemic.

South Korean President Moon jae-in held a State Council meeting in Blue House on the 18th, saying it was necessary to regard the economic impact of the new pneumonia outbreak as an "economic emergency, " and that emergency measures should be taken in an emergency, and instruct the department concerned to take effective measures in two aspects of guaranteeing national security and people's livelihood economy.

Moon said South Korea would bear the brunt of any deterioration in China's economic situation, which has already affected supplies and production activities related to China. It is even predicted that this outbreak will have a greater and longer impact on South Korea than previous SARS and Mers outbreaks.

Moon also said that besides China, the worsening epidemic in Japan is one of the variables, and it is important for the epidemic in neighboring countries to stabilize as soon as possible in order to get rid of the cross-border spread of infectious diseases, he called on relevant departments to make more efforts in cooperation and relief with the international community, and to join hands with neighboring countries to tide over the difficulties.

Starting Feb. 17, Seoul's Lotte World Tower, the country's tallest skyscraper and a famous landmark, will light up China. Every night between 18 and 22:00 hours and at 30:00, the 555-meter-high facade of the building will be lit with Chinese and English subtitles of "Go Wuhan! " To show support for China's fight against the new pneumonia. According to the Chinese Embassy in South Korea, the "light support" will last for ten days.
